<div class="contact-double-page">

  <!-- COLONNE GAUCHE : TEXTE EDITORIAL -->
  <div class="contact-left">
    <div class="contact-left-inner">

      <!-- Label -->
      <p class="contact-label text-uppercase">
        Contact
      </p>

      <!-- Titre principal -->
      <h1 class="contact-main-title">
        Contact &<br>
        collaborations
      </h1>

      <!-- Chapo -->
      <p class="contact-chapo">
        This page illustrates how a dedicated contact space can connect an artist
        with curators, galleries, the press and audiences, while remaining coherent
        with a magazine-inspired layout.
      </p>

      <!-- Texte principal -->
      <div class="contact-body">
        <p>
          In a real artist website, this section would centralise all practical
          information: who to contact for exhibitions, which gallery represents
          the artist, how to request images or organise a talk, and how to stay
          informed about upcoming projects.
        </p>

        <p>
          Here, it serves as an example of how a contact page can stay clear and
          functional without losing its visual identity. A visitor should
          immediately understand how to reach the right person, whether they are
          a curator, journalist, collector or simply an admirer of the work.
        </p>

        <p>
          The actual form and contact details can be fully customised for each
          artist or cultural project, while keeping this editorial structure.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- COLONNE DROITE : IMAGE (COMME ABOUT / EXHIBITIONS) -->
  <div class="contact-right">
    <%= image_tag "artemisia-cover.jpg", class: "contact-image" %>
  </div>

</div>

